Wrote Python script "assign_hrt_hk_status_to_all_human_genes.py" on 22.05.26 to read all genes from "biomart_export_HumanAllGenes_220526.tsv" and all hk genes from "biomart_export_HRTatlashkgenelist_ENSGlength180526.tsv" Calculating the genelength of all genes.
    Also attributing hk status as HK or nonHK to all entries of a combined table. Non-HK genes were defined as all protein-coding genes on the main chromosomes 1–22, X and Y that were not part of the HRT Atlas HK gene set. 
    Consequently MT, alternative scaffolds, patches, haplotype regions, non-standard contigs, duplicate/alternative genomic annotations was filtered out. The final table is called "human_all_genes_with_hrt_atlas_hk_status.tsv" and contains 20084 Genes.

Wrote Python script "check_hrt_atlas_rescue_mappings.py" on 22.05.26 to check what happened to the 38 ENSG entries recovered by HGNC symbol rescue mapping from the 35 previously unmapped HRT Atlas ENST IDs.
    The script uses the rescue mapping table "biomart_export_HRTAtlas_35unmappedENST_HGNCsymbol_rescueMapping_toENSG_geneCoords_200526.tsv", which contains Gene stable ID, Gene start (bp), Gene end (bp), and Chromosome/scaffold name.
    It compares these rescue-mapped ENSG entries against the final table "human_all_genes_with_hrt_atlas_hk_status.tsv".
    The script checks whether each rescue gene is already present as HK, present as non-HK, or absent from the final gene table. If they are absent - thats prob. due to being filtered out so they stay out, if they are presen as HK nothing is added. If they are present as non-HK i need to investigate whether they can be added.

Wrote Python script "missingENSG_toHRT_rescue_refseq_ccds_matches.py" on 25.05.26 to check whether the rescue-mapped ENSG entries from the previously unmapped HRT Atlas ENST IDs could be clearly linked back to original HRT Atlas entries.
    Before this step, 35 HRT Atlas ENST IDs were not recovered in the original ENST-to-ENSG BioMart mapping. A rescue mapping via HGNC symbols had recovered 38 ENSG entries, of which 20 were present in the final human all-gene table as non-HK and therefore possible rescue candidates.
    To check these candidates more strictly, the 20 rescue ENSG IDs were used in Ensembl 115 BioMart, Human genes (GRCh38.p14), and exported as "biomart_export_humanHK_rescuemappedENSG_toENST_CCD_RefSeq250526.tsv" on 25.05.26.
    This BioMart export contained the attributes: Gene stable ID, Transcript stable ID, CCDS ID and RefSeq mRNA ID.
    The script uses this BioMart export and compares its RefSeq mRNA IDs and CCDS IDs against the original HRT Atlas file "Housekeeping_GenesHuman_HRTatlas.tsv", which contains ENST ID, Gene.name/HGNC symbol, RefSeq ID and CCDS ID.
    The goal was to avoid adding rescue-mapped genes blindly and to only accept mappings that can be linked unambiguously back to exactly one original HRT Atlas entry.
    The script produced 2 output tables "hrt_atlas_rescue_refseq_ccds_match_check_gene_level.tsv" and "hrt_atlas_rescue_refseq_ccds_match_summary_gene_level.tsv".
    Decision whther to add was made on ENSG/gene level, not on BioMart transcript-row level, because one ENSG can have many transcript, RefSeq or CCDS entries.
    Result: 16 rescue mappings were considered eligible because they matched unambiguously to one original HRT Atlas entry through RefSeq and/or CCDS. 4 rescue candidates were ignored/excluded because they were not sufficiently supported or were not unambiguous.
    This step was therefore useful because it recovered additional HRT Atlas HK genes while keeping the final HK/non-HK assignment conservative and traceable.

Wrote Python script "apply_hrt_atlas_rescue_hk_status.py" on 25.05.26 to apply the 16 unambiguous HRT Atlas rescue mappings to the final human gene-level HK/non-HK table.
    The script uses the table "human_all_genes_with_hrt_atlas_hk_status.tsv", which contains all human protein-coding main-chromosome genes with gene length and initial hk_status such as
    the gene rescue table "hrt_atlas_rescue_refseq_ccds_match_check_gene_level.tsv", where unambiguous rescue candidates were identified through RefSeq and/or CCDS matching.
    Only entries with the decision "eligible for rescue - unambiguous match to one original HRT Atlas entry" were chosen included/changed in status to HK.
    The updated final table is saved as "human_all_genes_with_hrt_atlas_hk_status_rescued.tsv".
    For transparency the script also creates "hrt_atlas_rescue_applied_log.tsv", to show (in the table) which genes were changed from non-HK to HK.
    This table should be the FINAL Human HK Gene mapping table - further Analysis in R.

